    title: "xpai 4K vs eufy Pet Camera (2026) — Budget No-Subscription Showdown",
    description: "xpai 4K UHD vs eufy Security Pet Camera head-to-head comparison. Both promise no monthly fees and local storage — but which budget pet camera delivers the best value in 2026?",
    winner: "The xpai 4K wins on pure hardware value — 4K resolution and 64GB built-in storage at $43 is unbeatable. But the eufy is the more polished, reliable choice with 2K resolution, 360° pan/tilt, motion tracking, and a mature app ecosystem. For general pet monitoring on a tight budget, get the xpai. If you want active tracking (auto-follow your pet), 360° room coverage, and a more refined experience, the eufy is worth the extra $86.",
    productAId: "xpai-4k-camera",
    productBId: "eufy-pet-cam",
    comparisonRows: [
      ["Price", "$43", "$129"],
      ["Resolution", "4K UHD (ultra-sharp)", "2K (sharp)"],
      ["Storage", "64GB built-in (free)", "MicroSD up to 128GB (~$15)"],
      ["Subscription", "None", "None"],
      ["Camera Movement", "Pan/Tilt", "360° Pan/Tilt + Auto Tracking"],
      ["Night Vision", "Yes (IR)", "Yes (IR)"],
      ["Two-Way Audio", "Yes", "Yes"],
      ["Motion Detection", "Basic alerts", "AI motion tracking + auto-follow"],
      ["Pet-Specific", "No (general security cam)", "No (general security cam)"],
      ["Warranty", "1 year", "1 year"],
    ],
    faqs: [
      { q: "Is 4K really necessary for a pet camera?", a: "Not strictly necessary, but at $43 it's a bonus. 4K means you can digitally zoom in 4x without losing clarity — useful for reading a pet's body language or checking if they got into something. The eufy's 2K is already sharper than 1080p and sufficient for most monitoring. For pet cameras specifically, 360° coverage and motion tracking matter more than raw resolution." },
      { q: "Which has better night vision?", a: "Both use infrared (IR) night vision and perform well in complete darkness up to about 30 feet. The xpai's 4K sensor gives it a slight edge in low-light detail, but in practice, both let you clearly see your pet sleeping or moving at night. Neither is a decisive winner here." },
      { q: "Can both cameras work without Wi-Fi?", a: "Both need Wi-Fi for live streaming and alerts. The xpai can record locally to its built-in 64GB storage even when Wi-Fi drops, but you won't get notifications. The eufy similarly records to SD card without internet. Neither offers offline live viewing — you need to be on the same network or using data." },
      { q: "Which is better for a multi-pet household?", a: "The eufy wins for multi-pet homes with its 360° pan/tilt and auto motion tracking — it can follow your pets as they move around the room. The xpai has pan/tilt but lacks auto-tracking, so you'll need to manually adjust the view. If you have multiple pets in different spots, the eufy's auto-follow is a real time-saver." },
    ],
  },
  "petkit-eversweet-vs-catit-pixi": {
    title: "PETKIT Eversweet vs Catit PIXI (2026) — Smart Fountain vs Smart Design?",
    description: "PETKIT Eversweet Solo 2 vs Catit PIXI Smart Fountain head-to-head. We compare noise levels, smart features, capacity, filter costs, and which fountain keeps your cat hydrated best.",
    winner: "The PETKIT Eversweet wins for most cat owners — it's quieter (30dB), has better app integration, lower long-term filter costs, and costs $20 less upfront. The Catit PIXI is the better choice if you want water intake tracking (unique to PIXI's app) and multiple drinking heights that accommodate cats of different sizes. For pure hydration performance and value, PETKIT. For health data enthusiasts and multi-cat homes with cats of varying sizes, Catit PIXI.",
    productAId: "petkit-eversweet",
    productBId: "catit-pixi",
    comparisonRows: [
      ["Price", "$59", "$79"],
      ["Rating", "★★★★½ (4.4)", "★★★★⅕ (4.2)"],
      ["Reviews", "7,200+", "3,800+"],
      ["Capacity", "2L", "3L"],
      ["Noise Level", "30dB (ultra-quiet)", "~35dB (quiet)"],
      ["Smart Features", "Filter replacement reminder", "Water intake tracking + LED"],
      ["Drinking Heights", "Single stream", "3 ergonomic heights"],
      ["Filter Type", "Multi-layer (PETKIT)", "Charcoal + foam (Catit)"],
      ["Filter Cost/Year", "~$25-35", "~$40-55"],
      ["Warranty", "1 year", "1 year"],
    ],
    faqs: [
      { q: "Which fountain is quieter?", a: "The PETKIT Eversweet is noticeably quieter at just 30dB — about the volume of a whisper. The Catit PIXI runs around 35dB, still quiet but you'll hear the water flow more distinctly. If the fountain is in a bedroom or quiet home office, PETKIT is the clear winner." },
      { q: "Is the Catit PIXI's water intake tracking useful?", a: "For health-conscious owners, yes — the PIXI's app estimates how much your cat drinks based on pump activity and water level changes. This can help detect early signs of kidney issues or diabetes, which are common in older cats. However, it's an estimate, not a precise measurement. If your cat has health concerns, it's a valuable extra layer of monitoring." },
      { q: "Which has cheaper long-term filter costs?", a: "PETKIT's multi-layer filters cost about $25-35/year (replacing every 4-6 weeks). Catit PIXI's filters run $40-55/year. Over 3 years, that's roughly a $45-60 difference — enough to nearly buy another PETKIT fountain. However, both are far cheaper than the cost of treating a dehydrated cat's urinary issues." },
      { q: "Do cats prefer one fountain over the other?", a: "The Catit PIXI has a unique advantage: 3 different drinking heights (stream, pool, and waterfall) that accommodate kittens, adult cats, and seniors in one fountain. The PETKIT's single-stream design is simpler. Most cats will drink from either, but multi-cat homes with cats of different sizes will find the PIXI's ergonomic design more universally accessible." },
    ],
  },
};

const data = compareMap[slug] || compareMap["litter-robot-4-vs-leos-loo-too"];

// Get products from products.json, or use inline data for generic comparisons
const productA = data.productAId ? allProducts.get(data.productAId) : data.productA;
const productB = data.productBId ? allProducts.get(data.productBId) : data.productB;
---

<BaseLayout title={data.title} description={data.description} type="article">
  <Breadcrumb crumbs={[{ label: "Compare", href: "/compare/" }, { label: productA.name + " vs " + productB.name }]} />

  <article>
    <h1 class="font-display text-3xl font-bold leading-tight text-forest md:text-4xl">{data.title}</h1>
    <p class="mt-3 text-lg leading-relaxed text-bark-muted">{data.description}</p>

    <Takeaways items={[
      `Winner: ${data.winner.substring(0, 100)}...`,
      `${productA.name} — $${productA.price} | ${productA.rating}★`,
      `${productB.name} — ${typeof productB.price === 'number' ? '$' + productB.price : productB.price} | ${productB.rating}★`,
      `${data.comparisonRows.length} features compared head-to-head`,
    ]} />

    <!-- Bottom Line -->
    <div class="mt-8 rounded-2xl border border-honey/30 bg-honey/5 p-6 md:p-8">
      <p class="text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-honey">Bottom Line</p>
      <p class="mt-2 font-display text-lg italic text-forest">"{data.winner}"</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Side by Side Cards -->
    <div class="mt-10 grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2">
      {[productA, productB].map((p, idx) => (
        <div class={`rounded-2xl border p-6 ${idx === 0 ? 'border-forest/20 bg-forest/3' : 'border-sage-dark/30 bg-white'}`}>
          <!-- Product image -->
          {p.imageUrl && (
            <img src={p.imageUrl} alt={p.name} class="mb-4 h-48 w-full rounded-xl object-cover bg-sage/60" loading="lazy" />
          )}
          <h2 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-forest">{p.name}</h2>
          <p class="text-sm text-bark-muted">by {p.brand}</p>
          <p class="mt-2 font-display text-3xl font-bold text-forest">{typeof p.price === 'number' ? '$' + p.price : p.price}</p>
          <div class="mt-4 space-y-2.5 text-sm">
            <p class="font-semibold text-green-800">Pros</p>
            {p.pros.map((pro: string) => <p class="text-green-800/80">&check; {pro}</p>)}
            <p class="mt-2 font-semibold text-rose-dark/80">Cons</p>
            {p.cons.map((con: string) => <p class="text-rose-dark/70">&times; {con}</p>)}
          </div>
          <a href={p.amazonUrl} target="_blank" rel="nofollow sponsored noopener"
             class="mt-5 inline-flex w-full items-center justify-center gap-2 rounded-xl bg-honey py-3 font-bold text-white shadow-sm transition-all hover:bg-honey-dark hover:shadow-md active:scale-[0.98]">
            View on Amazon
            <svg class="h-3.5 w-3.5" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2.5" d="M17 8l4 4m0 0l-4 4m4-4H3"/></svg>
          </a>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>

    <!-- Feature Comparison Table -->
    <div class="mt-10">
      <h2 class="mb-4 font-display text-xl font-bold text-forest">Feature Comparison</h2>
      <div class="overflow-x-auto rounded-2xl border border-sage-dark/30">
        <table class="w-full text-sm">
          <thead>
            <tr class="bg-sage/60">
              <th class="px-5 py-3.5 text-left font-semibold text-forest">Feature</th>
              <th class="px-5 py-3.5 font-semibold text-forest">{productA.name}</th>
              <th class="px-5 py-3.5 font-semibold text-forest">{productB.name}</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-sage-dark/20">
            {data.comparisonRows.map(([feature, a, b]) => (
              <tr class="bg-white transition-colors hover:bg-sage-light/50">
                <td class="px-5 py-3.5 font-medium text-bark">{feature}</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3.5 text-bark-muted">{a}</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3.5 text-bark-muted">{b}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>

    <FAQ items={data.faqs} />
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
